&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;Truant&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Truant&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; means &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;a pupil who stays away from school without leave or explanation&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;​Eg.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;At the time he had started&amp;nbsp;playing &lt;strong&gt;truant&lt;/strong&gt; at school,&amp;nbsp;his academic progress had been disrupted.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;According to the given meaning and example, the correct answer will be &lt;strong&gt;option 3 &amp;#39;Truant&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;​&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Let us learn the meanings of other words given in the options:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Delinquent:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;tending to commit crime, particularly minor crime.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Lazy teen:&lt;/strong&gt; a teenager who is&amp;nbsp;unwilling to work or use energy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Idler:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;a person who avoids work or spends time in an aimless or lazy way.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;born to riches and luxury&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Let&amp;#39;s understand the implication of the idiom:&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Born with a silver spoon in his mouth&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&amp;nbsp;to have a &lt;strong&gt;high social position and be rich&lt;/strong&gt; from birth.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Example: &lt;em&gt;Deepa&amp;nbsp;has always had the best of everything. She was &lt;strong&gt;born with a silver spoon in her mouth &lt;/strong&gt;and has never had to worry about money.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Example:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;Even though he was &lt;strong&gt;born with a silver spoon in his mouth&lt;/strong&gt;, Keshav has always been very down-to-earth and humble.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is apparent from the above explanation that the correct &lt;strong&gt;meaning of the idiom &amp;quot;born with a silver spoon in his mouth&amp;quot; is &amp;quot;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;born to riches and luxury&lt;/span&gt;&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is:&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;born to riches and luxury&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here are some &amp;quot;silver&amp;quot; idioms with examples:&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;E&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;very cloud has a silver lining:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt; &lt;/span&gt;even in difficult or negative situations, there is always a positive or hopeful aspect to be found.&amp;nbsp;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Example: &lt;em&gt;Every cloud has a silver lining, right? Even though he lost his work, he could spend more time with his family.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Silence someone with silver:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;To &lt;strong&gt;offer someone money in exchange for their silence &lt;/strong&gt;or cooperation is said to &amp;quot;silence someone with silver.&amp;quot;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Example:&lt;em&gt; The &amp;quot;whistleblower&amp;quot; refused to be bought off despite the company&amp;#39;s best efforts to silence him with silver.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;at the drop of a hat&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The idiom,&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;at the drop of a hat&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;generally means,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;em&gt;immediately; without having to stop and think about it&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;(तुरंत; एकदम, अतिशीघ्र)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So as per the meaning&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;at the drop of a hat&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;is the correct idiom to be used.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, the complete sentence would be,&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Once she has the credit card in her wallet, she purchases some of the most expensive&amp;nbsp;things&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;at the drop of a hat&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;em&gt; and then begins to worry about how to pay back.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;em&gt;Therefore, the&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;correct&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 2)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let&amp;#39;s look at the meanings of other idioms given in the options:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Under a hat:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;keep something a secret.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;With a hat in a hand:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;humbly asking for a favour.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Holding on to a&amp;nbsp;hat:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;An expression warning someone of a big surprise.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Calendar&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct spelling from the options is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Calendar&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The meaning of the word is-&amp;nbsp;A system of timekeeping that defines the beginning and length and divisions of the year (टाइमकीपिंग की एक प्रणाली जो वर्ष की शुरुआत और लंबाई और विभाजन को परिभाषित करती है)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The spelling of the other words is-&amp;nbsp;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Beggar, Sober, and Superior.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 2.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The students placed &lt;strong&gt;their&lt;/strong&gt; backpacks over &lt;strong&gt;there&lt;/strong&gt; outside the classroom before sitting for the exam.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The word &amp;quot;their&amp;quot; is a possessive pronoun indicating ownership, while &amp;quot;there&amp;quot; refers to a place.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Option 3 (&amp;quot;their; there&amp;quot;) correctly fills in the blanks with the appropriate words.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;​Therefore, the correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1 (there; there)&lt;/strong&gt;: Both instances use &amp;quot;there&amp;quot; indicating place, which is incorrect.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2 (their; their)&lt;/strong&gt;: Both instances use &amp;quot;their&amp;quot; indicating possession, which is incorrect.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 4 (there; their)&lt;/strong&gt;: The order is incorrect for the context of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;b&gt;Option 4&lt;/b&gt;&amp;nbsp;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Instead of&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; means in place of someone or something. (इसके बजाय)

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; She went to the party &lt;strong&gt;instead of &lt;/strong&gt;studying for her exams.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Slowing down&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; refers to reducing speed or taking a more leisurely pace. (धीमा करना)
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The car is &lt;strong&gt;slowing down&lt;/strong&gt; as it approaches the traffic light.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, the sentence should be structured as&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;Instead of slowing down when sighting an approaching car, some drivers tend to speed up.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;Instead of slowing down when&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here are the other options explained along with their Hindi meanings and example sentences:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;When instead of slowing down&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;जब इसके बजाय धीमा करने के&lt;/span&gt;): This phrase is grammatically incorrect and does not fit the sentence structure.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The phrase does not form a coherent sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Instead when slowing down at&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;इसके बजाय जब धीमा हो रहा हूँ&lt;/span&gt;): This phrase is awkward and does not convey the intended meaning properly.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; This sequence of words results in a fragmented and unclear sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;When instead of slowing down at&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;जब धीमा होने के बजाय&lt;/span&gt;): This phrase is also grammatically incorrect and does not make sense in English.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; This phrase does not form a meaningful sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Anxiety disorders differ from normal feelings of nervousness or anxiousness, and involve excessive fear or anxiety.&amp;#39; (Option 2)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h4&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Anxiety disorders differ from normal feelings of nervousness or anxiousness, and involve excessive fear or anxiety.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This option is grammatically correct. It uses the correct verb &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;differ&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; and the correct preposition &amp;quot;from&amp;quot; to describe the difference, and matches the plural subject with the plural verb &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;involve&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot;

		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Subject-Verb Agreement: &lt;/strong&gt;The plural subject &amp;quot;Anxiety disorders&amp;quot; is matched with the plural verb &amp;quot;differ,&amp;quot; maintaining agreement between the subject and verb.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Proper Use of Prepositions: &lt;/strong&gt;The verb &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;differ&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is correctly paired with the preposition &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;from&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; to indicate a difference between two or more things.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Parallel Structure&lt;/strong&gt;: The sentence uses parallelism by comparing &amp;quot;anxiety disorders&amp;quot; to &amp;quot;normal feelings of nervousness or anxiousness.&amp;quot; The conjunction &amp;quot;or&amp;quot; is used to connect two parallel structures, ensuring that the sentence flows well.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Comma Usage&lt;/strong&gt;: The comma after &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;anxiousness&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; separates two independent clauses. This comma, along with the conjunction &amp;quot;and,&amp;quot; helps the reader understand the relationship between the two parts of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Use of Articles:&lt;/strong&gt; The sentence uses the indefinite article &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;an&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; before &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;anxiousness&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; as it precedes a vowel sound.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Use of Adjectives&lt;/strong&gt;: The adjectives &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;excessive&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; and &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;normal&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; are used to describe and contrast the nouns they modify. &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Excessive&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; describes the fear or anxiety in anxiety disorders, while &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;normal&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; describes feelings of nervousness or anxiousness.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is Option 2.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Anxiety disorders different form normal feelings of nervousness or anxiousness, and involves excessive fear or anxiety.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Different form&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is incorrect; it should be &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;differ from.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Involves&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; should be &amp;quot;involve&amp;quot; to match the plural subject &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Anxiety disorders&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Anxiety disorders differ with normal feelings of nervousness or anxiousness, and excess fear or anxiety involved.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Differ with&amp;quot; i&lt;/strong&gt;s incorrect; &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;differ from&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is the proper expression.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The phrase &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;excess fear or anxiety involved&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is awkward and grammatically inconsistent with the rest of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Anxiety disorders are different from normal feelings of nervousness or anxiousness, and involving excessive fear or anxiety.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Involving&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is incorrect here; the verb should be &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;involve&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; to align with the subject.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;at&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the above question, we have to choose the correct preposition&amp;nbsp;to complete the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is &amp;quot;at.&amp;quot; This is because &amp;quot;at&amp;quot; is used to indicate a specific location, and in this sentence, the sister lives in the building located at the end of the crosscut road.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Over&amp;quot; is not appropriate because&lt;/strong&gt; it generally refers to a position above something. In this sentence, there is no indication that the building is above anything.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;On&amp;quot; is not appropriate because &lt;/strong&gt;it generally refers to a position above and touching the surface of something. In this sentence, there is no indication that the building is touching the surface of the road.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Since&amp;quot; is not appropriate because&lt;/strong&gt; it is a conjunction used to indicate a time period, and not a location. It is not a suitable preposition in this sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;​Thus, the correct answer is &amp;quot;at&amp;quot;&lt;/p&gt;

